00:02:31.329 --> 00:02:32.120
I am Dale Anderson.

00:02:32.120 --> 00:02:34.245
I work over at the SETI
Institute at the Carl Sagan

00:02:34.245 --> 00:02:35.040
Center.

00:02:35.040 --> 00:02:38.280
And I do look at life
in extreme environments,

00:02:38.280 --> 00:02:42.900
and I'll take you on a journey
to see some of those areas.

00:02:42.900 --> 00:02:45.080
Again, basically at
the SETI Institute

00:02:45.080 --> 00:02:47.420
we're interested in the
field of astrobiology,

00:02:47.420 --> 00:02:50.590
and these bigger questions
of how did we get here,

00:02:50.590 --> 00:02:53.510
where are we going,
and are we alone?

00:02:53.510 --> 00:02:55.880
Are there microbial
ecosystems out in the universe

00:02:55.880 --> 00:02:57.720
besides the ones we
find on Earth, or even

00:02:57.720 --> 00:03:01.230
perhaps intelligent life that
we can hear through the radio

00:03:01.230 --> 00:03:02.930
signals or other means?

00:03:02.930 --> 00:03:05.410
And then we have
quite a few people

00:03:05.410 --> 00:03:08.386
that work in a whole
slew of different areas.

00:03:08.386 --> 00:03:10.010
It's a very
multi-disciplinary approach

00:03:10.010 --> 00:03:12.384
to understanding the origins,
evolution, and distribution

00:03:12.384 --> 00:03:13.740
of life in the universe.

00:03:13.740 --> 00:03:16.700
So we're interested
in following the birth

00:03:16.700 --> 00:03:19.010
of the biogenic
elements in the stars

00:03:19.010 --> 00:03:22.280
all the way up through the
evolution of advanced life.

00:03:22.280 --> 00:03:25.480
And so we have to have knowledge
of both things out in space,

00:03:25.480 --> 00:03:27.670
and in particular we need
to have those lessons

00:03:27.670 --> 00:03:29.910
that we learned here on Earth.

00:03:29.910 --> 00:03:33.620
And of course, for us
right now, since we're not

00:03:33.620 --> 00:03:36.170
going to be able to get
out beyond the solar system

00:03:36.170 --> 00:03:38.230
anytime soon we're most
interested in trying

00:03:38.230 --> 00:03:42.640
to find life here in our own
neighborhood, places like Mars,

00:03:42.640 --> 00:03:45.630
and some of the outer moons
or outer planetary moons

00:03:45.630 --> 00:03:50.330
like Europa,
Enceladus, and Titan.

00:03:50.330 --> 00:03:54.430
So a little bit about me
and how I got to where I am.

00:03:54.430 --> 00:03:57.190
I've been working in remote
environments like this

00:03:57.190 --> 00:03:58.430
since I was 22.

00:03:58.430 --> 00:04:00.316
And that was back
in 1978, so I've

00:04:00.316 --> 00:04:02.030
been doing this for
a pretty good while.

00:04:02.030 --> 00:04:05.130
I've got about 17
seasons in Antarctica,

00:04:05.130 --> 00:04:09.020
60 plus months camped out
in these areas over my life.

00:04:09.020 --> 00:04:12.280
Another 30 field seasons or
so up north, with another 30

00:04:12.280 --> 00:04:13.087
months up there.

00:04:13.087 --> 00:04:15.170
So I've spent a lot of
time sleeping in the rocks,

00:04:15.170 --> 00:04:17.209
and have gotten pretty
comfortable at it,

00:04:17.209 --> 00:04:19.769
and really enjoy doing
that kind of work.

00:04:19.769 --> 00:04:22.222
And I've been able
over the years

00:04:22.222 --> 00:04:23.680
to help develop a
lot of techniques

00:04:23.680 --> 00:04:25.469
that we use to work
in these environments,

00:04:25.469 --> 00:04:27.260
particularly the diving
under the thick ice

00:04:27.260 --> 00:04:29.840
and putting the methods
together for studying

00:04:29.840 --> 00:04:30.730
those environments.

00:04:30.730 --> 00:04:34.220
And that's what I'm going to
talk about a little bit today.

00:04:34.220 --> 00:04:36.320
Let's see.

00:04:36.320 --> 00:04:38.483
