00:04:43.205 --> 00:04:44.955
So here's the map of
Antarctica, and we're

00:04:44.955 --> 00:04:47.210
going to go to basically
two different areas.

00:04:47.210 --> 00:04:48.720
I've had the
privilege of working

00:04:48.720 --> 00:04:50.659
in three major areas
of the Antarctic.

00:04:50.659 --> 00:04:52.200
Down in the bottom
part of the screen

00:04:52.200 --> 00:04:53.430
you'll see McMurdo
Sound, and that's

00:04:53.430 --> 00:04:56.050
where the US Antarctic program
and the New Zealand programs

00:04:56.050 --> 00:04:59.680
have their biggest research
programs going, right

00:04:59.680 --> 00:05:03.140
around Ross Island and
the McMurdo Dry Valleys.

00:05:03.140 --> 00:05:05.600
Also I've worked over in the
Bunger Hills, which is over

00:05:05.600 --> 00:05:09.080
on the right hand
side of the screen.

00:05:09.080 --> 00:05:11.170
This is another ice free area.

00:05:11.170 --> 00:05:16.070
Back in 1991, '92, I was
part of a joint expedition

00:05:16.070 --> 00:05:19.090
between the Soviet space program
and the US space program.

00:05:19.090 --> 00:05:21.080
We spent about six and
a half, seven months

00:05:21.080 --> 00:05:23.797
traversing around the Antarctic
continent by ice breaker,

00:05:23.797 --> 00:05:26.213
and then getting dropped off
in the Bunger Hills for four,

00:05:26.213 --> 00:05:28.014
four and a half months.

00:05:28.014 --> 00:05:29.555
It was almost like
a Mars simulation.

00:05:29.555 --> 00:05:33.650
You know, have an international
group of researchers,

00:05:33.650 --> 00:05:36.620
mostly Russian and
American, one Canadian,

00:05:36.620 --> 00:05:39.300
live together and work
together, and get over

00:05:39.300 --> 00:05:41.841
those cultural difficulties
and language barriers just

00:05:41.841 --> 00:05:44.090
as you would if you were on
Mars for a period of about

00:05:44.090 --> 00:05:44.740
three years.

00:05:44.740 --> 00:05:45.870
Really kind of a trip.

00:05:45.870 --> 00:05:48.090
So this was a great expedition
to do exobiology work

00:05:48.090 --> 00:05:50.190
with out Soviet counterparts.

00:05:50.190 --> 00:05:54.960
More recently I've started
working with Chris and Alfonso.

00:05:54.960 --> 00:05:56.640
Up in the top part
of the screen you'll

00:05:56.640 --> 00:05:59.080
see that where the arrow is
going up to Lake Untersee,

00:05:59.080 --> 00:06:01.610
this is down below South Africa.

00:06:01.610 --> 00:06:03.820
There's an area there called
the Schirmacher Oasis.

00:06:03.820 --> 00:06:06.660
And then you go further inland
and you'll hit some mountains.

00:06:06.660 --> 00:06:09.797
And this is where the lake
that we're studying is located.

00:06:09.797 --> 00:06:12.130
But I want to start this off
in the McMurdo Dry Valleys.

00:06:12.130 --> 00:06:16.550
This is down in the Ross Island
region, south of New Zealand,

00:06:16.550 --> 00:06:19.769
and this is were I cut my teeth
in the Antarctic back in 1978

00:06:19.769 --> 00:06:20.810
starting as an undergrad.

00:06:24.150 --> 00:06:25.540
Let me just back this up.

00:06:25.540 --> 00:06:28.590
So the McMurdo Dry Valleys
are the largest ice free area

00:06:28.590 --> 00:06:30.040
in the Antarctic continent.

00:06:30.040 --> 00:06:32.900
It's only about 1% of the
continent is actually ice free.

00:06:32.900 --> 00:06:35.040
So it's a very rare
type of environment.

00:06:35.040 --> 00:06:37.060
It's a very cold, dry place.

00:06:37.060 --> 00:06:39.600
And it's probably the
best terrestrial analog

00:06:39.600 --> 00:06:42.080
that we have on
the planet to Mars.

00:06:42.080 --> 00:06:44.530
And that's one of the things
that has drawn researchers

00:06:44.530 --> 00:06:47.890
there, even from
the early 1960s.

00:06:47.890 --> 00:06:50.810
JPL and Ames both had
researchers going down there

00:06:50.810 --> 00:06:54.966
to prepare for the Viking
Program for example.

00:06:54.966 --> 00:06:56.340
These were cold
deserts that they

00:06:56.340 --> 00:06:59.980
wanted to understand how to look
for microbiology at the time.

00:06:59.980 --> 00:07:01.790
So if you look very
closely in these values

00:07:01.790 --> 00:07:03.373
you'll see next to
the glaciers you'll

00:07:03.373 --> 00:07:05.680
see some ice covered bodies.

00:07:05.680 --> 00:07:07.844
And those are small
lakes in the valleys.

00:07:07.844 --> 00:07:09.260
And that's where
we're going to be

00:07:09.260 --> 00:07:11.650
doing some of our work
in a little while.

00:07:11.650 --> 00:07:16.420
Back in 1977 George
Simmons, who's

00:07:16.420 --> 00:07:17.950
standing above me
while I'm getting

00:07:17.950 --> 00:07:20.440
ready to jump in to
Lake Bonney here,

00:07:20.440 --> 00:07:23.010
asked this very interesting
and important question

00:07:23.010 --> 00:07:24.879
when he got out to these lakes.

00:07:24.879 --> 00:07:26.920
Traditionally people had
only drilled small holes

00:07:26.920 --> 00:07:28.378
through the thick
ice covers, cause

00:07:28.378 --> 00:07:31.410
the ice covers are anywhere from
3 and 1/2 to 6 meters thick.

00:07:31.410 --> 00:07:32.910
So that's a lot of
ice that you have

00:07:32.910 --> 00:07:34.957
to go through to
get to the water.

00:07:34.957 --> 00:07:36.540
Traditionally people
had drilled holes

00:07:36.540 --> 00:07:39.550
through those with a
small jiffy drill, which

00:07:39.550 --> 00:07:44.220
is a 20 centimeter, ten
inch bit to get through,

00:07:44.220 --> 00:07:46.330
but nobody ever looked at
the bottom of the lakes.

00:07:46.330 --> 00:07:48.040
Most of the work was done
in the water columns looking

00:07:48.040 --> 00:07:50.850
at the phytoplankton and things
that are growing in the water.

00:07:50.850 --> 00:07:52.892
But nobody actually
asked the question

00:07:52.892 --> 00:07:54.100
what's growing on the bottom?

00:07:54.100 --> 00:07:55.920
Most people thought
probably nothing,

00:07:55.920 --> 00:07:58.360
we'll probably just find
rocks, because light

00:07:58.360 --> 00:07:59.570
is going to be a limiter.

00:07:59.570 --> 00:08:01.834
The light has to
penetrate through the ice

00:08:01.834 --> 00:08:04.000
and go down to the bottom
to support photosynthesis,

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:05.780
and most people thought that
the light levels were just

00:08:05.780 --> 00:08:07.270
going to be simply too low.

00:08:07.270 --> 00:08:10.410
Simmons asked that
question, and it's funny

00:08:10.410 --> 00:08:12.310
because back in
those days we didn't

00:08:12.310 --> 00:08:14.199
have cameras the
size of my thumb

00:08:14.199 --> 00:08:15.990
like we do now that we
could just drop down

00:08:15.990 --> 00:08:17.198
that little jiffy drill hole.

00:08:17.198 --> 00:08:20.420
It was easier to take a
student, or somebody like George

00:08:20.420 --> 00:08:22.300
or myself, and drop
us down a bigger hole.

00:08:22.300 --> 00:08:24.292
And that's what we did.

00:08:24.292 --> 00:08:26.500
So this is going to be a
little bit about that story,

00:08:26.500 --> 00:08:30.080
how we got out there, and how we
started working in those lakes.

00:08:30.080 --> 00:08:31.730
And the biggest
single problem that we

00:08:31.730 --> 00:08:33.490
faced that first
year was how do you

00:08:33.490 --> 00:08:38.830
get through six meters of ice
to study those ecosystems.

00:08:38.830 --> 00:08:41.576
Now out in McMurdo Sound people
had been diving in the ocean

00:08:41.576 --> 00:08:43.159
there for years, and
years, and years.

00:08:43.159 --> 00:08:44.650
And this is actually
my favorite place

00:08:44.650 --> 00:08:45.880
on the planet to go swimming.

00:08:45.880 --> 00:08:49.040
The Antarctic ocean is
just stunningly beautiful

00:08:49.040 --> 00:08:49.610
underwater.

00:08:49.610 --> 00:08:52.230
And I've had the opportunity
to spend quite a bit of time

00:08:52.230 --> 00:08:55.300
under the ice in McMurdo Sound,
and I would be there right now

00:08:55.300 --> 00:08:56.140
doing it if I could.

00:08:56.140 --> 00:08:59.050
It's just that great of a place.

00:08:59.050 --> 00:09:01.450
It's easy to make a
dive hole in McMurdo.

00:09:01.450 --> 00:09:03.060
You just take a
big track vehicle

00:09:03.060 --> 00:09:04.820
out to where you
want to put the hole,

00:09:04.820 --> 00:09:06.950
and this hydraulic
drill just pops up,

00:09:06.950 --> 00:09:10.960
and it's got a 1 and 1/2
meter diameter bit on it,

00:09:10.960 --> 00:09:14.441
you just pop it
over, and take off,

00:09:14.441 --> 00:09:16.690
and about a half hour later
you've got a hole drilled,

00:09:16.690 --> 00:09:18.580
and then you just
clear the ice out.

00:09:18.580 --> 00:09:20.500
And then you can even
pull a little hut

00:09:20.500 --> 00:09:22.602
over the top with
a heater inside.

00:09:22.602 --> 00:09:24.060
You've got this
nice house that you

00:09:24.060 --> 00:09:26.268
can sit in, get all your
dive gear on and everything,

00:09:26.268 --> 00:09:27.230
and then go swimming.

00:09:27.230 --> 00:09:28.813
The only thing you
have to do is share

00:09:28.813 --> 00:09:30.890
the dive hole
occasionally with seals.

00:09:30.890 --> 00:09:31.990
And of course that's
one of those things

00:09:31.990 --> 00:09:33.960
that you have to be careful
about because there's not

00:09:33.960 --> 00:09:36.376
a lot of room in a dive hole,
and if you've got to get out

00:09:36.376 --> 00:09:38.980
and the seal's there
that can be a problem.

00:09:38.980 --> 00:09:41.720
But it is an incredibly
gorgeous place underwater.

00:09:41.720 --> 00:09:43.680
I just through love it.

00:09:43.680 --> 00:09:49.359
It's filled with life, and the
lighting is just beautiful,

00:09:49.359 --> 00:09:51.400
and there's ice, anchor
ice, all over the bottom.

00:09:51.400 --> 00:09:55.170
There's frazil ice underneath
the sea ice itself.

00:09:55.170 --> 00:09:56.670
It's one of those
things that if you

00:09:56.670 --> 00:10:00.830
get to watch some of the
videos that are online

00:10:00.830 --> 00:10:05.132
and on BBC right now you should
definitely do it if you can.

00:10:05.132 --> 00:10:08.090
Now, back in the early '90s
we had a Telepresent Rover

00:10:08.090 --> 00:10:09.660
that we were using.

00:10:09.660 --> 00:10:11.970
We actually had this Rover
connected back to NASA Ames

00:10:11.970 --> 00:10:15.480
by satellite so that we could
control it through Ames so they

00:10:15.480 --> 00:10:16.890
could make virtual
dives with me.

00:10:16.890 --> 00:10:20.660
So Butler Hine and several
others, Michael Sims,

00:10:20.660 --> 00:10:22.630
over at Ames would actually
go swimming with me

00:10:22.630 --> 00:10:23.963
while they were in their office.

00:10:23.963 --> 00:10:28.090
And I would be 11, 12,000
miles away underwater

00:10:28.090 --> 00:10:29.290
underneath the ice.

00:10:29.290 --> 00:10:32.140
And we also had the opportunity
to turn that episode

00:10:32.140 --> 00:10:36.030
into an EPO opportunity.

00:10:36.030 --> 00:10:40.270
And we had students in
California, Hawaii and Virginia

00:10:40.270 --> 00:10:43.980
also drive this vehicle and take
virtual dives with me as well.

00:10:43.980 --> 00:10:46.960
So this was in November
of 1993, and at that time

00:10:46.960 --> 00:10:51.680
I was actually pulling together
a little program called

00:10:51.680 --> 00:10:52.475
Dale's Dive Diary.

00:10:52.475 --> 00:10:56.400
And we were pumping this up
through Quest here at NASA Ames

00:10:56.400 --> 00:10:59.960
on to the very, very
new web at the time.

00:10:59.960 --> 00:11:03.230
So we've been kind to
actively involved in trying

00:11:03.230 --> 00:11:06.962
to blog and get our stories
out since the first time

00:11:06.962 --> 00:11:08.170
that we could actually do it.

00:11:08.170 --> 00:11:11.480
And this was actually the first
time any broadcast like this

00:11:11.480 --> 00:11:14.137
had been made from
the Antarctic.

